[USER] Great, thank you! How can I include an equation in the document?

[ASSISTANT] You can include an equation in your LaTeX document by wrapping it in dollar signs `$` for inline equations or double dollar signs `$$` for display equations. For example, the equation $E=mc^2$ can be written in LaTeX as `$E=mc^2$`. For more complex equations, you can use the `equation` environment. Here is an example of a display equation:$$\begin{equation}
E = \frac{mc^2}{\sqrt{1 - \frac{v^2}{c^2}}}
\end{equation} $$This equation represents the relativistic energy of an object with mass $m$ and velocity $v$.

[USER] Thank you! Now, how can I include a figure in my LaTeX document?

[ASSISTANT] To include a figure in your LaTeX document, you can use the `\includegraphics` command from the `graphicx` package. The syntax is `\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{path/to/image.extension}`. This command will insert the image at its original size. You can adjust the size of the image using the optional `width` or `height` parameter. Here is an example of how to include a figure in your LaTeX document:```\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{path/to/image.extension}
\caption{Your figure caption goes here.}
\end{figure} ```The `\centering` command centers the image on the page, and the `\caption` command adds a caption below the image. The `figure` environment will automatically number the figure and place it in the most appropriate location in the document.
